  "text": "Investigation of Particleâˆ’Particle Interaction (Structure Factor). The thickness of polymer shells grafted to NPs is highly dependent on the solvent, which is crucial to their functionality in biological environments. Measurements were carried out in MQ water and buffer solutions. Figure 4 shows a typical scattering curve from a coreâˆ’shell particle in water and exhibits two distinct features; one in the high q-range from 0.23âˆ’0.42 Ã… âˆ’1 , which can be attributed to the core signal (cf. Figure 3) , and a shoulder in the region of 0.12 Ã… âˆ’1 . Similar shoulders have been reported in the literature. Various interpretations have been put forward ranging from particleâˆ’particle interactions (structure factor) [CITATION_1] to dumbbell formation. [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] Therefore, a dilution series was carried out to ascertain that the shoulder could not be attributed to concentration-dependent particleâˆ’particle interaction (such as hard sphere interaction); a lower concentration will shift the peak position to smaller q if the shoulder results from particleâˆ’ particle interactions.",
